===Etymology 1===
{{PIE root|en|gʷʰedʰ}}
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|bidden}}, from the {{etyl|ang|en}} verb {{m|ang|biddan||ask, demand}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*bidjaną||to ask}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*gʷʰedʰ-}}. Conflated with the {{etyl|ang|en}} verb {{m|ang|bēodan||offer, announce}} (see Etymology 2 below). Compare West Frisian {{m|fy|bidde}}, Low German {{m|nds|bidden}}, Dutch {{m|nl|bidden}} ("to pray"), German {{m|de|bitten}}, Danish {{m|da|bede}}, {{cog|no|be}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|bids|bidding|bid|past2=bade|past3=bad|bid|past_ptc2=bidden}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To issue a [[command]]; to [[tell]].
#: ''He '''bade''' me to come in.''
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[invite]]; to [[summon]]; to [[pray for]]; to [[offer]].
#: ''She was '''bidden''' to the wedding.''
#: '''Bid''', Lord, a blessing.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[utter]] a [[greeting]] or [[salutation]].

=====Usage notes=====
The inflected forms {{m|en|bade}}, {{m|en|bad}}, and {{m|en|bidden}} are archaic. They remain in marginal use, particularly regarding greetings, as in “bade farewell”, but uninflected '''bid''' is significantly more common, and {{m|en||bidden}} is especially rare.<ref>“[http://grammarist.com/usage/bid-bade-bidden/ Bid, bade, bidden]”, ''Grammarist''</ref>

When it does occur, it is usually in an elevated, ironical or metaphorical style e.g "I have '''bidden''' farewell to my prospects of promotion."

When '''bade''' or '''bad''' is used in formal speech the pronunciation /bæd/ may be heard.  However, when a dated text is being read or recited (e.g. on stage, in school or in church etc.) /beɪd/ is quite usual.

